The paper proposes a formal graph-theoretic model for studying the problem of matching rides online in a ride-sharing platform. This problem involves online matching in non-bipartite graphs, which is a topic in graph theory and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses edge-weighted and vertex-weighted versions of the model, which are topics in graph theory and optimization (cs.GT). The algorithms proposed in the paper use randomized and primal-dual analysis techniques, which are topics in artificial intelligence and machine learning (cs.AI, cs.LG). Finally, the paper discusses the practical application of the model in ride-sharing platforms, which is a topic in social and information networks (cs.SI).
